<BaseLayout
  title="Monday — Luna | Nazaryah"
  description="The day-name Monday comes from Luna, the Roman moon goddess. Here is who she was and why mapping her day onto Yahuah's calendar is a mistake."
>
  <article class="pg">
    <div class="pg-inner">

      <a href="/calendar" class="pg-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to the Calendar</span></a>

      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Monday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Luna</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Roman moon goddess</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Monday on the Gregorian calendar honors the moon-goddess of Rome. Her name was <strong>Luna</strong>, and she was worshiped across the Roman world as the divine personification of the moon — the counterpart to Sol, the sun-god whose day comes just before hers.
      </p>

      <h2>Who She Was</h2>

      <p>
        Luna was the Roman name for the moon as a deity. The Greeks called her Selene. The Babylonians called her Sin. The Egyptians knew her as Khonsu and Thoth. Across the pagan world, the moon was given a personal name and worshiped as a goddess — credited with controlling fertility, the tides, women's bodies, and the rhythms of the night.
      </p>

      <p>
        Luna was paired with Sol as a divine couple. Where Sol ruled the day, Luna ruled the night. Romans built temples to her, dedicated horses and chariots to her in imitation of the moon's monthly travels, and held festivals in her honor. The Roman day of the moon was called <em>dies Lunae</em> — the day of Luna. When the Germanic peoples adopted the Roman week, they translated the name directly: Old English <em>Mōnandæg</em>, "Moon's day," becoming Monday.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Moon-worship is condemned alongside sun-worship throughout Scripture. Yahuah did not separate the two as if one were less serious than the other.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 4:19</span> — "And lest thou lift up thine eyes unto heaven, and when thou seest the sun, and the moon, and the stars, even all the host of heaven, shouldest be driven to worship them, and serve them…"
      </div>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Job 31:26–28</span> — "If I beheld the sun when it shined, or the moon walking in brightness; And my heart hath been secretly enticed, or my mouth hath kissed my hand: This also were an iniquity to be punished by the judge: for I should have denied Elohim that is above."
      </div>

      <p>
        Job names it directly. To behold the moon and let his heart be drawn into reverence for her would have been a denial of Yahuah Himself. The moon is beautiful. The moon faithfully marks the months. But the moon is a created vessel — the lesser light hung in the firmament on the fourth day. Honoring her with a day-name treats the servant as if she were the master.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        A common reaction is to ask: <em>"What day in Yahuah's calendar is Monday really?"</em> The question is misplaced.
      </p>

      <p>
        Monday is a Roman day named after a Roman moon-goddess. It belongs to Babylon's clock — the continuous seven-day rotation tied to pagan deities. Yahuah's clock does not have a Monday. Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are numbered, and the Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>There is no Monday in this system.</strong> Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the names a pagan world stamped onto a continuous seven-day rotation. The Roman week and Yahuah's reckoning are two different clocks, running on different principles, and they do not translate into each other.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Monday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it. But knowing the origin matters. The moon Yahuah created to mark His months — the lesser light, the faithful witness in the heavens — was given a goddess's name in the Roman world and a goddess's day on the calendar. The pagan world gave the credit for the moon's faithfulness to a creature instead of to the Creator who made her.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a moon-goddess tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Monday is Luna's day. The moon in the sky is not Luna — she is the lesser light Yahuah hung in the firmament on the fourth day of creation, and she answers only to the One who made her.
      </div>

      <div class="pg-closing">
        <a href="/calendar" class="pg-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to the Calendar</span></a>
      </div>

    </div>
